summary: Sleep came hard, even when Daario came back, so drunk that he could hardly stand. Beneath her coverlets she tossed and turned,...
caption: Sleep came hard, even when Daario came back, so drunk that he could hardly stand. Beneath her coverlets she tossed and turned, dreaming that Hizdahr was kissing her … but his lips were blue and bruised, and when he thrust himself inside her, his manhood was cold as ice. She sat up with her hair disheveled and the bedclothes atangle. Her captain slept beside her, yet she was alone. She wanted to shake him, wake him, make him hold her, fuck her, help her forget, but she knew that if she did, he would only smile and yawn and say, “It was just a dream, my queen. Go back to sleep.”

summary: What are the chances that D&D went for mad queen Dany in order to cover up an arguably even more controversial ending like...
question: What are the chances that D&D went for mad queen Dany in order to cover up an arguably even more controversial ending like Daenerys dying in childbirth?
answer: Pretty low, in my opinion. If Dany has a child in the books, there’s every reason for her to live past that point and make the decisions to risk and eventually sacrifice herself for the sake of her child’s future. The inverse of Stannis’ likely situation.

summary: “Breaking the wheel” and my ideal ending to Game of Thrones.
title: “Breaking the wheel” and my ideal ending to Game of Thrones.
body:
One of the many things that pissed me off about the GoT finale (and season 8 in general) was how D&D chose to end Daenerys’ storyline. I know iT wAs FoReShAdOwEd she would go mad and that she will share the same fate in the books. However, even though evidence kind of pointed at Dany dying in the end and loosing her mind I have my own idea of how her story should’ve ended.

In the 8th episode of the fifth season Daenerys delivers one of her most famous quotes (and one of the most famous in the show overall):

Lannister, Baratheon, Stark, Tyrell. They’re all just spokes on a wheel. This one’s on top, then that one’s on top, and on and on it spins, crushing those on the ground… I’m not going to stop the wheel, I’m going to break the wheel.

A few episodes later, in season 6, Dario tells Daenerys the following words:

You weren’t made to sit on a chair in a palace. You are a conqueror, Daenerys Stormborn.

When I first saw 5x08 I understood the “I’m not going to stop the wheel, I’m going to break the wheel” quote as Daenerys affirming she would end the long cycle of conqueror-conquered which was a bit odd to me because, after all, she wanted to be Queen of the Seven Kingdoms. Like @misseffie mentioned on this ask she answered a couple of days ago, another Targaryen sitting on the throne would only mean more of the same.

However, after Dario’s quote from 6x06 and because GoT loved foreshadowing, I had a revelation that maybe both scenes were heavily related and here’s why:

When Aegon conquered the Seven Kingdoms he pretty much forced them to come together under his rule. They were all the Targaryens’ “slaves”, sort to speak. Daenerys experienced first hand how much the northerners longed for independence and how resentful they were of her for being a Targaryen, as they remembered what had happened the last time a Targaryen had brought dragons to the North.

Here’s where my ideal ending scenario begins.

After the Great War Daenerys understands the northerners motivations and realizes maybe her claiming the Iron Throne isn’t a very good idea after all because she’ll just be more of the same, no real change and no breaking the wheel. Instead, in her condition of Breaker of Chains she would make it her mission to free the people of the Seven Kingdoms not from Cersei’s reign, but from the idea of the Iron Throne itself. After defeating Cersei in King’s Landing and pretty much conquering the Seven Kingdoms—as Aegon did—she would claim the throne but only for a little while, and she would proclaim the dissolution of the realm and it getting reorganized into nine independent regions:

  • The North (ruled by Sansa Stark)
  • The Riverlands (ruled by Edmure Tully)
  • The Iron Islands (ruled by Yara Greyjoy)
  • The Vale (ruled by Robin Arryn)
  • The Westerlands (ruled either by Jaime or Tyrion Lannister)
  • The Reach (ruled by someone other than Bronn, probably Davos Seaworth)
  • The Stormlands (ruled by Gendry Baratheon)
  • Dorne (ruled by whoever is head of House Martell now)
  • The Crownlands (there’s no clear heir to this region so Daenerys would give the people the option of choosing their ruler, and they would choose her. She would rename it the Dragonlands)

That way, in some sort of poetic cinema, Daenerys would destroy what his ancestor created. She would break the wheel built by Aegon himself, fulfilling the promise she made in season 5. Full circle.

This is how I would’ve loved GoT to end. I know it was a pipe dream but hey, I had a dream.
